ayers]]\n[[Category:Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Panathinaikos B.C. players]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Union City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Union Hill High School alumni]]\n[[Category:1986 FIBA World Championship players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            = Nikos Galis\n| image           = \u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03ba\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2.jpg\n| image_size      = 180\n| caption         = Nikos Galis with [[Aris B.C.|Aris]], in the late 1980s.\n| position        = \n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 0\n| weight_lb       = 199\n| team            =\n| league          =\n| nationality     = Greek / American\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1957|07|23}}\n| birth_place     = [[Union City, New Jersey]]\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| high_school     = [[Union Hill High School|Union Hill]]<br />(Union City, New Jersey)\n| college         = [[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball|Seton Hall]] (1975\u20131979)\n| draft_year      = 1979\n| draft_round     = 4\n| draft_pick      = 68\n| draft_team      = [[Boston Celtics]]\n| career_position = [[Shooting guard]]\n| career_number   = 6, 4\n| career_start    = 1979\n| career_end      = 1994\n| years1          = 1979\u20131992\n| team1           = [[Aris B.C.|Aris]]\n| years2          = 1992\u20131994\n| team2           = [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]\n| highlights      = \n* 8\u00d7 [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] champion (1983, 1985\u20131991)\n* 7\u00d7 [[Greek Basketball Cup|Greek Cup]] winner (1985, 1987\u20131990, 1992, 1993)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Greek Basket League MVP|Greek League MVP]] (1988\u20131992)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Greek Basket League Finals MVP|Greek League Finals MVP]] (1987\u20131991)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Greek Basketball Cup MVP|Greek Cup Finals Top Scorer]] (1987, 1989, 1990, 1992, 1993)\n* [[FIBA EuroBasket MVP]] ([[EuroBasket 1987|1987]])\n* 11\u00d7 [[List of top scorers in Greek Basket League by season|Greek League Top Scorer]] (1981\u20131991)\n* 8\u00d7 [[FIBA EuroLeague Top Scorer]] (1986\u20131992, 1994)\n* 4\u00d7 [[Greek Basket League statistical leaders|Greek League assists leader]] (1991\u20131994)\n* [[EuroLeague individual statistics|EuroLeague assists leader]] ([[Euroleague 1993-94|1994]])\n* [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]] (2008)\n* [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] (1991)\n* No. 6 [[Aris B.C.#Retired numbers|retired by Aris]]  (2013)\n* [[FIBA European Selection]] (1987)\n* [[Euroscar Award]] (1987)\n* [[Mr. Europa Award]] (1987)\n* Mediterranean Player of the Year (1987)\n* [[Seton Hall]] Athletic Hall of Fame (1991)\n* [[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]] Player of the Year (1979)\n* [[Haggerty Award]] (1979)\n| HOF             = \n| HOF_player      = nick-galis\n| HOF_coach       = \n| FIBA_HOF_player = Nikos-Galis\n| medaltemplates  = \n{{MedalCountry | {{bk|GRE}} }}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[EuroBasket 1987|1987 Greece]] | }}\n{{MedalSilver| [[EuroBasket 1989|1989 Yugoslavia]] | }}\n}}\n'''Nikolaos Galis''' (''[[n\u00e9]]'' '''Georgalis''') ({{lang-el|\u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03bb\u03b1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03ba\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2}}; born July 23, 1957<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedraftreview.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=5076|title=The Draft Review|first=Fine Line Websites & IT|last=Consulting|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>), commonly known as either '''Nikos Galis''' ({{lang-el|\u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03ba\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2}}), or '''Nick Galis''', is a retired Greek professional [[basketball]] player. He was named one of [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players (1991)|FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] in 1991, is an inaugural member of the [[FIBA Hall of Famer|FIBA Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.halloffame.fiba.com/pages/eng/hof/indu/play/2007/p/lid_17904_newsid/19959/bio.html/ |title=FIBA Hall Of Fame Class of 2007 |access-date=2007-06-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707073724/http://www.halloffame.fiba.com/pages/eng/hof/indu/play/2007/p/lid_17904_newsid/19959/bio.html/ |archive-date=2007-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was chosen as one of the [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/item/24016|title=Euroleague official website, ''Experts decide European Club Basketball's 50 greatest contributors''}}</ref> \nGalis is widely regarded as one of [[Europe|Europe's]] greatest scorers to ever play the game, as well as one of the all-time greatest players in [[FIBA]] international basketball history.{{efn|See<ref name=\"fibaeurope.com\">Psarakis, Yannis, Fibaeurope.com, Nikos Galis - Europe's Greatest - Ever Scorer [http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_N27pw3E0IEQwyW1SY,jjq1.coid_TAEWX2DlJdkjxfsVfUULa3.articleMode_on.html]</ref><ref name=\"euroleague.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/features/voices/2011-2012/vladimir-stankovic/i/91124/nikos-gallis-a-scoring-machine|title=Nikos Gallis, a scoring machine|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/coid_TcU1iWLAI,EZ-oLXXo5xm2.articleMode_on.html|title=European Legends Pay Tribute To Galis  - FIBA Europe|website=www.fibaeurope.com|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>}} In 2017, he was inducted into the [[List of players in the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame|Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/19052994/tracy-mcgrady-bill-self-rebecca-lobo-headline-2017-basketball-hall-fame-class|title=McGrady, Self, Lobo headline 2017 HOF class|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018|date=April 2017}}</ref>\n\nGalis played the [[point guard]] position during his [[college basketball]] years at [[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball|Seton Hall University]], but turned into a [[shooting guard]] as a [[professional sports|professional]]. He spent most of his career in [[Aris BC|Aris]], before having a late stint with [[Panathinaikos BC|Panathinaikos]]. He is the [[EuroLeague]]'s all-time leader in points per game (counting both [[FIBA Europe]] and [[Euroleague Basketball Company]] era games [[1958 FIBA European Champions Cup|1958 season]]\u2013present), [[EuroLeague Top Scorer|leading the competition in scoring]] eight times. In [[EuroLeague|the premier European club scene]], he reached the [[EuroLeague Final Four]] on four occasions, three consecutive times with Aris ([[1988 EuroLeague Final Four|1988]], [[1989 EuroLeague Final Four|1989]], and [[1990 EuroLeague Final Four|1990]]), and another one with Panathinaikos ([[1994 EuroLeague Final Four|1994]]). An eight-time [[Greek Basket League|Greek league]] champion, Galis is the [[Greek Basketball Championship career statistical leaders#A National Category all-time stats leaders (since the 1963\u201364 season) (unofficial)|Greek Championship's unofficial all-time leading scorer]], in both career points scored and career scoring average, counting all league formats (since the 1963\u201364 season, [[Greek Basket League career stats leaders|official stats are recognized since the 1992\u201393 season]]).\n\nGalis led the senior [[Greece national basketball team|Greek national team]] to a [[EuroBasket]] gold medal in [[EuroBasket 1987|1987]], as well as to a EuroBasket silver medal in [[EuroBasket 1989|1989]], earning the [[FIBA EuroBasket MVP|tournament MVP]] honor in 1987, and being elected to the [[FIBA EuroBasket All-Tournament Team|All-EuroBasket Team]] four times. Among his myriad accomplishments, he holds the [[FIBA EuroBasket Records|EuroBasket record]] for highest career scoring average (31.2 points per game), and was [[FIBA EuroBasket Top Scorer|the leading scorer of four EuroBasket tournaments]] in [[EuroBasket 1983|1983]], [[EuroBasket 1987|1987]], [[EuroBasket 1989|1989]], and [[EuroBasket 1991|1991]]. In addition to that, he holds the [[FIBA Basketball World Cup|FIBA World Championship/Cup]] [[FIBA World Cup records|record]] for highest career scoring average (33.5 points per game), as well as for most points ever scored in a single tournament, which he set at the [[1986 FIBA World Championship]]. Following the stunning success of the EuroBasket title in 1987, he won the [[Mr. Europa|Mr. Europa Player of the Year]] and the [[Euroscar Award|Euroscar]] awards the same year.\n\nNicknamed \"Iron Man\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_wro9VQVdG7cxqdc3r6woH2.coid_OetsMywJJtcKppVVZ6xGT3.articleMode_on.html|title=Iron Man Galis - FIBA Europe|website=www.fibaeurope.com|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> \"Nick The Greek\",<ref name=\"interbasket.net\">{{cite web|url=http://www.interbasket.net/players/galis.htm|title=Nikos Galis, Greece - Player Profiles by Interbasket|website=www.interbasket.net|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> and \"The Gangster\",<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090618125309/http://www.geocities.com/nikosgalis/aris1.html Nikos Galis Aris]</ref> Galis is highly revered in [[Greece]], where he is considered by many to be the greatest national athlete the country has ever seen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fe/10/fwcm/event-guide/p/nid/41921/legend-bio.html|title=FIBA.com, Greece-Nick Galis.|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> His years at Aris lifted [[Basketball in Greece|Greek basketball]] from relative obscurity, to global power status, with Galis being the figure that eventually inspired thousands of Greeks to take up the game.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">Maguire, Ken, Nytimes.com, Basking in a Fonder Farewell, 19 Years Later [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/14/sports/basketball/aris-honors-nick-galis-a-hero-of-greek-basketball.html?_r=0]</ref>\n\n==Early life and high school==\nGalis was born in [[Union City, New Jersey]]. The child of a poor immigrant family, from the Greek islands of [[Rhodes]] and [[Nisyros]], Galis took up [[boxing]] in his early years, after his father, George Georgalis, who had also been a boxer in his youth. He was later persuaded to give up boxing by his mother, Stella Georgalis, who was terrified after each time that her son would return home from boxing training with a new facial injury. As a result, Galis started playing the sport of basketball instead of boxing. He attended [[Union Hill High School]], in Union City, where he also played high school basketball.<ref name=\"fibaeurope.com\"/>\n\n==College career==\nAfter high school, Galis enrolled at [[Seton Hall University]], where he played [[college basketball]] as a member of the [[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball|Seton Hall Pirates]]. In his senior season, Galis saw his scoring average reach 27.5 points per game, which was third in the nation, behind [[Idaho State Bengals men's basketball|Idaho State's]] [[Lawrence Butler (basketball)|Lawrence Butler]] (30.1 points per game) and [[Indiana State Sycamores men's basketball|Indiana State's]] [[Larry Bird]] (28.6 points per game),<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Magic Keeps Bird In Hand |url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1123258/index.htm |work=Sports Illustrated |publisher= |date=1980-03-13 |accessdate= }}</ref> including a 48-point outburst against the [[Santa Clara Broncos men's basketball|University of Santa Clara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://graphics.fansonly.com/photos/schools/sacl/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/cablecar-history-12300.pdf|title=Cable Car Classic Records.|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlso in his senior year of college, Galis won the [[Haggerty Award]] (the New York City metro area's best player award), and the [[Eastern College Athletic Conference]] Player of the Year award. The same year, he also played in the Pizza Hut All-American game, alongside Bird and [[Vinnie Johnson]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Galis and Larry Bird (Pizza Hut All American Game 1979) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PUdOiTjIcxo |work=Youtube|publisher= |date=2010-03-10 |accessdate= }}</ref> During his 4-year college career, Galis played in a total of 107 games and scored 1,651 points, for a career scoring average of 15.4 points per game.<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/nick-galis-1.html|title=Nick Galis College Stats - College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nGalis' head coach at Seton Hall, [[Bill Raftery|Billy Raftery]], would later state that Galis was the best player he ever coached. While at Seton Hall, Galis was a good friend and roommate of [[Italian-American]] professional basketball player [[Dan Callandrillo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.app.com/story/sports/college/2017/09/08/insane-nick-galis-journey-naismith-hall-fame-took-off-seton-hall/646390001/|title=For 'insane' Nick Galis, journey to Naismith Hall of Fame took off at Seton Hall|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> Galis was later inducted into the [[Seton Hall]] Athletic Hall of Fame, in 1991.\n\n===College stats===\n<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\"/>\n{| bgcolor=\"#f7f8ff\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" style=\"font-size: 95%; border: gray solid 1px; border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" \n| align=\"center\"|'''Season'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''Team'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''Competition'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Games Played]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Field goal percentage|Field Goal%]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Free throw|Free Throw%]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Points per game|Points]]'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EFEFEF\" align=left\n|<center>1975\u201376</center>\n|<center>[[Seton Hall Pirates men's basketball|Seton Hall]]</center>\n|<center>[[College basketball|NCAA D-I]]</center>\n|<center>24</center>\n|<center>47.5</center>\n|<center>70.4</center>\n|<center>1.1</center>\n|<center>1.8</center>\n|<center>3.2</center>\n|-align=left\n|<center>1976\u201377</center>\n|<center>Seton Hall</center>\n|<center>NCAA D-I</center>\n|<center>29</center>\n|<center>38.1</center>\n|<center>81.9</center>\n|<center>2.3</center>\n|<center>4.8</center>\n|<center>12.6</center>\n|- bgcolor=\"#EFEFEF\" align=\"left\"\n|<center>1977\u201378</center>\n|<center>Seton Hall</center>\n|<center>NCAA D-I</center>\n|<center>27</center>\n|<center>52.1</center>\n|<center>82.6</center>\n|<center>2.4</center>\n|<center>4.5</center>\n|<center>17.3</center>\n|-align=left\n|<center>1978\u201379</center>\n|<center>Seton Hall</center>\n|<center>NCAA D-I</center>\n|<center>27</center>\n|<center>57.6</center>\n|<center>82.6</center>\n|<center>3.5</center>\n|<center>3.9</center>\n|<center>27.5</center>\n|- bgcolor=\"#EFEFEF\" align=\"left\"\n|'''Career Totals'''\n|<center>Seton Hall</center>\n|<center>NCAA D-I</center>\n|<center>'''107'''</center>\n|<center>'''50.0'''</center>\n|<center>'''81.7'''</center>\n|<center>'''2.4'''</center>\n|<center>'''3.8'''\n\n'''</center>\n|<center>'''15.4'''</center>\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n===Boston Celtics===\nAfter finishing his collegiate career in 1979, Galis signed with agent Bill Manon, who also managed [[Diana Ross]]. Manon did not have Galis work out with any [[NBA]] team.<ref name=\"interbasket.net\"/> Galis was eventually selected by the [[Boston Celtics]] in the 4th round of the [[1979 NBA Draft]], 68th overall. Due to a severe ankle injury that Galis suffered during the [[Boston Celtics|Celtics]] preseason training camp of the [[1979\u201380 Boston Celtics season|1979\u201380 season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2017/08/31/euroleague-legend-nikos-galis-made-mark-five-greek-league-mvp-awards|title=2017 Hall of Fame: Euroleague legend, cast of NCAA standouts get their due - NBA.com|first=Scott|last=Howard-Cooper|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> the franchise was no longer interested in offering him a contract because [[Gerald Henderson]] had taken his place on the team, and his injury would keep him out for the foreseeable future.\n\nGalis then decided to pursue a professional career in [[Greece]]'s top-tier level [[Greek Basket League|Basket League]]. Later, while still playing in Greece, he would be offered [[NBA]] contracts by the Celtics and the [[New Jersey Nets]]. However, he turned the offers down, because at the time, and until 1989, [[FIBA]] did not have [[professional sports|professional]] status, and consequently did not allow NBA players to compete at the [[national sports team|national team]] level. Since playing with the senior [[Greek national basketball team|Greek national team]] meant so much to him, he stayed in Greece. Celtics then-president [[Red Auerbach]] later said that the single biggest mistake he ever made in his career was not keeping Galis.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://turkey2010.fiba.com/pages/eng/fe/10/fwcm/event-guide/p/nid/41921/legend-bio.html |title=Fiba official website, Tribute to Nikos Galis |access-date=2010-10-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107144242/http://turkey2010.fiba.com/pages/eng/fe/10/fwcm/event-guide/p/nid/41921/legend-bio.html |archive-date=2010-11-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celticslife.com/2011/10/top-5-celtics-that-never-were-5-nick.html|title=Top 5 Celtics That Never Were-   #5: Nick Galis|website=www.celticslife.com|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Aris Thessaloniki===\n[[File:Nikos Galis Keith Williams.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Galis (on the right), and [[Keith Williams (basketball)|Keith Williams]] (on the left), during a [[EuroLeague]] [[1991\u201392 FIBA European League|1991\u201392 season]] game.]]\n\nAfter suffering an ankle injury in the [[Boston Celtics]] [[1979\u201380 Boston Celtics season|1979\u201380]] preseason training camp, which prevented him from receiving a contract with the Celtics, Galis made the move across the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]], and signed to play with [[Aris BC|Aris]] of [[Thessaloniki]], Greece, in 1979. [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]] and [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]] had also shown some interest in signing the newcomer, but it was Aris' interest that was the most persuasive. His move to the country would eventually help Greek [[sports club|club]] basketball to reach a level of popularity that had never been previously imagined.\n\nAveraging more than 30 points per game every season, Galis was the indisputable leader of Aris. While playing alongside other great players at Aris such as [[Panagiotis Giannakis]] and [[Slobodan Suboti\u0107]] (who was known in Greece as Lefteris Soumpotits), Galis won 8 [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] championships (7 of them consecutively, and 3 undefeated, in the years 1983, 1985, 1986, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1990, and 1991), 6 [[Greek Basketball Cup|Greek Cups]] (4 of them consecutively, in the years 1985, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1990, and 1992), and led Aris to 3 consecutive appearances at the [[EuroLeague|FIBA European Champions' Cup]] (now called EuroLeague) [[EuroLeague Final Four|Final Four]] ([[1988 EuroLeague Final Four|'88]], [[1989 EuroLeague Final Four|'89]], and [[1990 EuroLeague Final Four|'90]]). In the one disappointment of an otherwise glittering career with Aris, all three of the FIBA European Champions' Cup Final Four appearances ended in defeat in the semifinals, thus depriving Galis of the opportunity to shine all the way on Europe's biggest club stage, at the [[EuroLeague Finals|FIBA European Champions' Cup Finals]]. The team's performances and general standard of play, however, won the hearts of most basketball fans in Greece. Indeed, cinemas and theaters in Greece would often reduce their admission prices on Thursday evenings, when Aris was playing games, as large segments of the country settled down to watch them on television.\n\nAfter a disappointing season in 1991\u201392, Galis was forced to leave Aris.<ref>Rabotas, G., ''Nikos Galis'', p. 137</ref> The new management of the team, and the fact that the club was in decline, were the main causes for his departure. Galis, who adored the city of [[Thessaloniki]], had originally insisted on remaining in the club and playing for the team, as he believed that he still had a lot to offer the club. In one of his final European Champions' Cup games for Aris, in early-1992, Galis rolled back the years, at the age of 35, to score 46 points (15/18, 8/14, 5/6) in a narrow defeat to Phillips Milan. Also that season, in a Greek league match against Panionios, Galis scored 48 points on 12/13, 15/18, 2/3.\n\n===Panathinaikos Athens===\n[[Image:Nikos Galis Panathinaikos 1992.jpg|right|thumb|160px|Galis with [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]], during the 1992\u201393 season.]]\n\nGalis moved to [[Athens]] in the summer of 1992, to play with [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]], and he was the player who then led the \"Greens\" to a club rebirth, after it had suffered through a long drought period, during which the historical team remained without titles. The previous season (1991\u201392) had been particularly disappointing for the club, with the team finishing eighth in the Greek league. As the team's [[Captain (sports)|captain]], Galis inspired the young players of Panathinaikos, such as [[Fragiskos Alvertis]] and [[Nikos Oikonomou]], and gradually brought back hope to the team's fans. So much so, as to the point that the club's then home arena, [[Glyfada Indoor Hall]], was always overcrowded. In that season (1992\u201393), Panathinaikos finished second in the [[Greek Basket League|Greek league]], and won the [[Greek Basketball Cup|Greek Cup]], which was the seventh Greek Cup title for Galis.\n\nThe following season ([[1993\u201394 FIBA European League|1993\u201394]]), Galis was the FIBA European League (now called EuroLeague) [[EuroLeague Top Scorer|Top Scorer]] averaging 23.8 points per game in 21 games, and passer, averaging 4.7 assists per game, in 21 games. In the decisive game 3 of the EuroLeague quarterfinals, against the reigning [[EuroLeague|FIBA European League]] champions, [[Limoges CSP|Limoges]], Galis truly led Panathinaikos into a new club era, with their qualification to the [[1994 EuroLeague Final Four|1994 FIBA European League Final Four]], by scoring 30 points on 75% field goal shooting in the game. The \"Greens\" eventually finished in 3rd place in the FIBA European League that season, after losing in the semifinal, but it was still a success they had never reached before. Galis scored 30 points in the third place game against [[FC Barcelona B\u00e0squet|FC Barcelona]], leading all scorers in the game.\n\nIn his third season in Panthinaikos ([[1994\u201395 FIBA European League|1994\u201395]]), Galis teamed up with [[Panagiotis Giannakis]] and [[\u017darko Paspalj]], to make a strong effort to win the FIBA European League. Galis was the player who led Panathinaikos to the Top 16 group, as he prevented the elimination of Panathinaikos by [[Budivelnik Kiev]], with a team-high 23 points in the decisive second-leg victory. He was also the leader of the team in the [[Greek Basketball Cup|Greek Cup]] win against [[Olympiacos B.C.|Olympiacos]], at [[Sporting Sports Arena]]. But Galis' career controversially ended on October 18, 1994,<ref>[http://www.gazzetta.gr/basket/a1/item/105797-\u0397\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd-\u03b1\u03c0\u03bb\u03ac-\u03bf-\u03ba\u03b1\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 Gazetta.gr \u0389\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd \u03b1\u03c0\u03bb\u03ac \u03bf \u03ba\u03b1\u03bb\u03cd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 {{in lang|el}}.]</ref> a few games after the start of the Greek League 1994\u201395 season. [[Kostas Politis]], Panathinaikos' head coach at the time, chose not to include Galis in the starting line-up of a [[Greek Basket League|Greek League]] game against [[Ampelokipoi B.C.|Ambelokipi]]. Galis left the court, and never again returned to playing action.<ref>Rabotas, G., ''Nikos Galis'', p. 195</ref> His last game in professional basketball, was as a player of Panathinaikos, in a game against [[Dafnis B.C.|AO Dafni]], on October 12, 1994. In the game, Galis scored 8 points in 35 minutes of playing time, as his team won in a blowout, 82\u201360.\n\n=== Career pro club statistics ===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_Rrcja7ZFIJoKfuh7kQ,-F3.coid_TAEWX2DlJdkjxfsVfUULa3.articleMode_on.html|title=Nikos Galis \u2013 Europe's Greatest-ever Scorer - FIBA Europe|website=www.fibaeurope.com|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"basket.gr\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.basket.gr/archive/players/BestPlayer.asp?PlayerCode=101 |title=basket.gr \u039f\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03c0\u03ce\u03bd\u03c5\u03bc\u03bf: \u0393\u039a\u0391\u039b\u0397\u03a3 \u039d\u0399\u039a\u039f\u03a3 |language=el |access-date=2007-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406075936/http://www.basket.gr/archive/players/BestPlayer.asp?PlayerCode=101 |archive-date=2007-04-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sansimera.gr/biographies/279|title=\u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0393\u03ba\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n{| bgcolor=\"#f7f8ff\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" style=\"font-size: 95%; border: gray solid 1px; border-collapse: collapse;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" \n| align=\"center\"|'''Competition'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Games Played]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Point (basketball)|Points Scored]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''[[Points per game|Scoring Average]]'''\n| align=\"center\"|'''Ref.'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#EFEFEF\" align=left\n|[[Greek Basket League|Greek League]]\n|<center>385</center>\n|<center>12,714</