{"title_page": "Codex Argenteus", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|Gothic bible translation}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Wulfila_bibel.jpg|thumb|A page of the Codex Argenteus]]\nThe '''Codex Argenteus''' ([[Latin]] for \"Silver Book/Codex\") is a 6th-century manuscript, originally containing [[Gospel#Canonical gospels|part]] of the [[Gothic Bible|4th-century translation of the Bible]] into the [[Gothic language]]. Traditionally ascribed to bishop [[Ulfilas]], it is now established that the Gothic translation was performed by several scholars, possibly under Ulfilas's supervision.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ratkus|first1=Art\u016bras|title=Greek \u1f00\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03cd\u03c2 in Gothic translation: Linguistics and theology at a crossroads|journal=NOWELE|date=2018|volume=71|issue=1|pages=3\u201334|doi=10.1075/nowele.00002.rat|url=https://benjamins.com/#catalog/journals/nowele.00002.rat/details}}</ref> Of the original 336 folios, 188&mdash;including the Speyer fragment discovered in 1970&mdash;have been preserved, containing the translation of the greater part of the four [[gospel]]s. A part of it is on permanent display at the [[Carolina Rediviva]] building in [[Uppsala|Uppsala, Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Bruce M. |last=Metzger |author-link=Bruce M. Metzger |title=The Early Versions of the New Testament |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1977 |page=378}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Origin===\nThe \"Silver Bible\" was probably written for the [[Ostrogoths|Ostrogothic]] King [[Theodoric the Great]], either at his royal seat in [[Ravenna]], or in the [[Po River|Po valley]] or at [[Brescia]]. It was made as a special and impressive book written with gold and silver ink on high-quality thin [[Purple parchment|vellum stained a regal purple]], with an ornate [[treasure binding]]. After Theodoric's death in 526 the Silver Bible is not mentioned in inventories or book lists for a thousand years.\n\n===Discovery===\nParts of the \"Codex Argenteus\" (literally, \"Silver Book\"), 187 of the original 336 parchment folia, were preserved at the former Benedictine [[Werden Abbey|abbey of Werden]] (near [[Essen]], Rhineland). The abbots at Werden were imperial princes and had a seat in the [[Imperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Diet]]. While the precise date of the \"Silver Bible\" is unknown, it was discovered at Werden in the 16th century.\n\nThe codex, or the remaining part of it, came to rest in the library of Holy Roman Emperor [[Rudolph II]] at his imperial seat in [[Prague]].<ref>[http://www.ub.uu.se/arv/codexeng.cfm Uppsala University Library] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041208110615/http://www.ub.uu.se/arv/codexeng.cfm/ |date=2004-12-08 }}</ref> At the end of the [[Thirty Years' War]], in 1648, after the [[Battle of Prague (1648)|Battle of Prague]], it was taken as war booty to [[Stockholm]], Sweden, to the library of Queen [[Christina of Sweden]]. After her conversion to [[Catholicism]] and her abdication, the book went to the [[Netherlands]] among the property of [[Isaac Vossius]], her former librarian, in 1654. In the 1660s, it was bought and taken to [[Uppsala University]] by Count [[Magnus Gabriel De la Gardie]], who also provided its present lavishly decorated binding.\n\nThe codex remains at the [[Uppsala University Library]] in the Carolina Rediviva building. On 5 April 1995, parts of the codex that were on public display in Carolina Rediviva were stolen. The stolen parts were recovered one month later, in a storage box at the [[Stockholm Central Station|Stockholm Central Railway Station]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Thomas |last=Totte |url=http://www.kb.se/dokument/Aktuellt/audiovisuellt/N%C3%A5gra%20hyll%28nings%29centimeter/473-484TottieKuppen.pdf |publisher=[[National Library of Sweden]] |title=Kuppen mot Silverbibeln |access-date=27 March 2017 |language=Swedish}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | first= Lena |last=K\u00f6ster | url = http://www.unt.se/kultur/mysterier-kring-silverbibeln-1794931.aspx | title = Mysterier kring Silverbibeln | newspaper=[[Upsala Nya Tidning]] |date=2012-07-15 |access-date=27 March 2017 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nThe details of the codex's wanderings for a thousand years remain a mystery; it is unknown whether the other half of the book may have survived.\n\nIn 1998 the codex was subjected to [[Radiocarbon dating|carbon-14 analysis]] and was dated to the sixth century.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://wwwc.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/9804/07/telegram/inrikes8.html |newspaper=[[Aftonbladet]] |title=Silverbibeln daterad med kol-14-metoden |trans-title=Codex Argenteus carbon date determined |location=Uppsala |agency=TT |date=7 April 1998 |access-date=27 March 2017 |language=Swedish}}</ref> It was also determined that the manuscript had been bound at least once during the sixteenth century.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla64/050-132e.htm |title=Silver Bindings carbon dated |access-date=September 24, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319110406/http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla64/050-132e.htm |archive-date=March 19, 2015 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n===The Speyer fragment===\nThe final leaf of the codex, fol. 336, was discovered in  October 1970 in [[Speyer|Speyer, Germany]], 321&nbsp;km south-east of Werden. It was found at the restoration of the  [[Saint Afra]] chapel, rolled around a thin wooden staff, contained in a small [[reliquary]]{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} <!--whos bones contained this reliquary?--> originating in [[Aschaffenburg]]. The leaf contains the final verses of the [[Gospel of Mark]].\n\n===Publications===\nFirst publication mentioning Gothic manuscript appeared in 1569 by [[Goropius Becanus]] in his book ''Origines Antwerpianae'':{{quote|text=So now let us come to another language, which the judgement of every man of distinguished learning at Cologne identifies as Gothic, and examine the aforesaid Lord's Prayer written in that [language] in a volume of great age belonging to the monastery of Werden in the district of Berg, about four miles from Cologne. This [volume] was kindly made available to me, with his notable generosity towards all researchers, by the most reverend and learned [[Maximilien Morillon]], from among the papers of his late brother Antoine.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l0n8QL3crpYC&printsec=frontcover&hl=pl&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Origines Antwerpianae''], Liber VII. Gotodanica: Ex officina Christophori Plantini, 1569, p. 740.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1597, [[Bonaventura Vulcanius]], [[Leiden]] professor of Greek, published his book ''De literis et lingua Getarum sive Gothorum''. It was the first publication of a Gothic text altogether, calling the manuscript \"Codex Argenteus\":\n\n{{quote|text=In regard to this Gothic language, there have come to me [two] brief dissertations by an unidentifiable scholar - shattered planks, as it were, from the shipwreck of the Belgian libraries; the first of these is concerned with the script and pronunciation [of the language], and the other with the Lombardic script which, as he says, he copied from a manuscript codex of great antiquity which he calls \"the Silver\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GRA8AAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=De+litteris+et+lingua+Getarum&hl=pl&sa=X&ei=LFYcUbzyMan14QTW8oHYCA&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false ''De literis et lingua Getarum''], 1597, p.4. Note that according to this Vulcanius did not himself invent the epithet 'Argenteus' but found it in the notes of an unidentified precursor.</ref>}}\n\nBut he was not only the first who enabled the learned world to make the acquaintance of the Gothic translation of the Gospels in Gothic script, but also the first who connected this version with the name of Ulfilas:\n\n{{quote|text=With all due respect to these writers, I should think that the use of Gothic scripts existed among the Goths long before the time of Wulfila but that it was he who first made it known to the Romans by translating the Holy Bible into the Gothic language.  I have heard that a manuscript copy of this, and a very ancient one, written in Gothic capital letters, is lurking in some German library.<ref>''De literis et lingua Getarum'', 1597, p.3</ref>}}\n\n[[Image:Oratio Dominica.jpg|thumb|Part of Lord's Prayer from ''De Literis & Lingva GETARUM Sive GOTHORUM'', 1597, p.33.]]\nIn his book Vulcanius published two chapters about the Gothic language which contained four fragments of the Gothic New Testament: the Ave Maria (Luke I.28 and 42), the Lord's Prayer (Matt. VI.9-13), the Magnificat (Luke I.46-55) and the Song of Simeon (Luke II.29-32), and consistently gave first the Latin translation, then the Gothic in Gothic characters, and then a transliteration of the Gothic in Latin characters.\n\nIn 1737, [[Lars Roberg]], a physician of Uppsala, made a [[woodblock printing|woodcut]] of one page of the manuscript; it was included in [[Henric Benzelius|Benzelius]]' edition of 1750, and the woodcut is preserved in the [[Link\u00f6ping]] Diocesan and Regional Library. Another edition of 1854&ndash;7 by [[Anders Uppstr\u00f6m]] contained an artist's rendition of another page. In 1927, a facsimile edition of the Codex was published.\n\nThe standard edition is that published by [[Wilhelm Streitberg]] in 1910 as ''Die Gotische Bibel'' (''The Gothic Bible'').\n\n==Script and illumination==\n[[File:Detail of Codex Argenteus.jpg|thumb|Detail of Codex Argenteus, Mt 5:34 scan of the 1927 facsimile edition. The highlighted section is an abbreviation of the Gothic cognate of \"[[God (word)|God]]\".]]\nThe manuscript is written in an [[uncial]] script in the [[Gothic alphabet]], reportedly created by [[Ulfilas]].  The script is very uniform, so much so that it has been suggested that it was made with stamps.  However, two hands have been identified: one hand in the Gospels of Matthew and John and another in the Gospels of Mark and Luke. The [[Illuminated manuscript|illumination]] is limited to a few large, framed initials and, at the bottom of each page, a silver arcade which encloses the monograms of the four evangelists.\n\n==Contents==\n\n*[[Gospel of Matthew]]: Matthew 5:15-48; 6:1-32; 7:12-29; 8:1-34; 9:1-38; 10:1,23-42; 11:1-25; 26:70-75; 27:1-19,42-66.\n*[[Gospel of John]]: 5:45-47; 6:1-71; 7:1-53; 8:12-59; 9:1-41; 10:1-42; 11:1-47; 12:1-49; 13:11-38; 14:1-31; 15:1-27; 16:1-33; 27:1-26; 28:1-40; 29:1-13.\n*[[Gospel of Luke]] 1:1-80; 2:2-52; 3:1-38; 4:1-44; 5:1-39; 6:1-49; 7:1-50; 8:1-56; 9:1-62; 10:1-30; 14:9-35; 15:1-32; 16:1-24; 17:3-37; 18:1-43; 19:1-48; 20:1-47.\n*[[Gospel of Mark]]: 1:1-45; 2:1-28; 3:1-35; 4:1-41; 5:1-5; 5-43; 6:1-56; 7:1-37; 8:1-38; 9:1-50; 10:1-52; 11:1-33; 12:1-38; 13:16-29; 14:4-72; 15:1-47; 16:1-12 (+ 16:13-20).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gothic Bible]]\n* [[Gothic language]]\n* [[Purple parchment]]\n* [[Codex Carolinus]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book | title = Codex argenteus Upsalensis jussu Senatus Universitatis phototypice editus | location = Uppsala | year = 1927}}\n* {{Cite book | author = T\u00f6nnes Kleberg | title = The Silver Bible at Uppsala | publisher = Uppsala University Library | location = Uppsala | year = 1984 | isbn = 91-85092-20-7}}\n* {{Cite book | author = Bologna, Giulia | title = Illuminated Manuscripts: The Book before Gutenberg | location = New York | publisher = Crescent Books | year = 1995 | page = 50}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Codex Argenteus}}\n*[http://www.ub.uu.se/about-the-library/exhibitions/codex-argenteus/ Homepage of the Codex Argenteus (Uppsala University Library)]\n*[http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:alvin:portal:record-60279 Digital copy of the Codex Argenteus in the Swedish portal for cultural heritage collections, alvin-record:60279]\n*[http://www.wulfila.be/ Wulfila Project] digital library dedicated to the study of Gothic\n* Lars Munkhammar, [https://web.archive.org/web/20150319110406/http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla64/050-132e.htm Uppsala University Library, \"Codex Argenteus\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041209053449/http://www.cs.tut.fi/~dla/Codex_Argenteus/Cod_Arg_Bib.html Codex Argenteus Bibliography]\n*[[oldwikisource:Die gotische Bibel|The Gothic Bible]] on [[Wikisource]], Streitberg's edition\n*[http://wikisource.org/wiki/Gothic_Bible_in_Ulfilan_Gothic_Script_with_correct_i Gothic Bible in Gothic script] on Wikisource\n*[http://la.wikisource.org/wiki/Patrologia_Latina_Vol_18_Ulfilas_-_Evangelia the Gothic New Testament] on wikisource, Patrologia Latina edition\n\n[[Category:6th-century biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:6th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Illuminated biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Purple parchment]]\n[[Category:Gothic Bible]]\n[[Category:Ostrogothic Kingdom]]\n[[Category:History of Uppsala]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date = February 2019}}\n{{Short description|Gothic bible translation}}\n{{Use American English|date = February 2019}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Wulfila_bibel.jpg|thumb|A page of the Codex Argenteus]]\nThe '''Codex Argenteus''' ([[Latin]] for \"Silver Book/Codex\") is a 6th-century manuscript, originally containing [[Gospel#Canonical gospels|part]] of the [[Gothic Bible|4th-century translation of the Bible]] into the [[Gothic language]]. Traditionally ascribed to bishop [[Ulfilas]], it is now established that the Gothic translation was performed by several scholars, possibly under Ulfilas's supervision.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ratkus|first1=Art\u016bras|title=Greek \u1f00\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03b5\u03c1\u03b5\u03cd\u03c2 in Gothic translation: Linguistics and theology at a crossroads|journal=NOWELE|date=2018|volume=71|issue=1|pages=3\u201334|doi=10.1075/nowele.00002.rat|url=https://benjamins.com/#catalog/journals/nowele.00002.rat/details}}</ref> Of the original 336 folios, 188&mdash;including the Speyer fragment discovered in 1970&mdash;have been preserved, containing the translation of the greater part of the four [[gospel]]s. A part of it is on permanent display at the [[Carolina Rediviva]] library in [[Uppsala]], [[Sweden]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Bruce M. |last=Metzger |author-link=Bruce M. Metzger |title=The Early Versions of the New Testament |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1977 |page=378}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Origin===\nThe \"Silver Bible\" was probably written for the [[Ostrogoths|Ostrogothic]] King [[Theodoric the Great]], either at his royal seat in [[Ravenna]], or in the [[Po River|Po]] valley or at [[Brescia]]. It was made as a special and impressive book written with gold and silver ink on high-quality thin [[Purple parchment|vellum stained a regal purple]], with an ornate [[treasure binding]]. After Theodoric's death in 526 the Silver Bible is not mentioned in inventories or book lists for a thousand years.\n\n===Discovery===\nParts of the \"Codex Argenteus\" (literally, \"Silver Book\"), 187 of the original 336 parchment folia, were preserved at the former Benedictine [[Werden Abbey|abbey of Werden]] (near [[Essen]], Rhineland). The abbots at Werden were imperial princes and had a seat in the [[Imperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Diet]]. While the precise date of the \"Silver Bible\" is unknown, it was discovered at Werden in the 16th century.\n\nThe codex, or the remaining part of it, came to rest in the library of Holy Roman Emperor [[Rudolph II]] at his imperial seat in [[Prague]].<ref>[http://www.ub.uu.se/arv/codexeng.cfm Uppsala University Library] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041208110615/http://www.ub.uu.se/arv/codexeng.cfm/ |date=2004-12-08 }}</ref> At the end of the [[Thirty Years' War]], in 1648, after the [[Battle of Prague (1648)|Battle of Prague]], it was taken as war booty to [[Stockholm]], Sweden, to the library of Queen [[Christina of Sweden]]. After her conversion to [[Catholicism]] and her abdication, the book went to the [[Netherlands]] among the property of [[Isaac Vossius]], her former librarian, in 1654. In the 1660s, it was bought and taken to [[Uppsala University]] by Count [[Magnus Gabriel De la Gardie]], who also provided its present lavishly decorated binding.\n\nThe codex remains at the [[Uppsala University Library]] in the [[Carolina Rediviva]] building. On 5 April 1995, parts of the codex that were on public display in Carolina Rediviva were stolen. The stolen parts were recovered one month later, in a storage box at the [[Stockholm Central Station|Stockholm Central Railway Station]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Thomas |last=Totte |url=http://www.kb.se/dokument/Aktuellt/audiovisuellt/N%C3%A5gra%20hyll%28nings%29centimeter/473-484TottieKuppen.pdf |publisher=[[National Library of Sweden]] |title=Kuppen mot Silverbibeln |access-date=27 March 2017 |language=Swedish}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | first= Lena |last=K\u00f6ster | url = http://www.unt.se/kultur/mysterier-kring-silverbibeln-1794931.aspx | title = Mysterier kring Silverbibeln | newspaper=[[Upsala Nya Tidning]] |date=2012-07-15 |access-date=27 March 2017 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nThe details of the codex's wanderings for a thousand years remain a mystery; it is unknown whether the other half of the book may have survived.\n\nIn 1998 the codex was subjected to [[Radiocarbon dating|carbon-14 analysis]] and was dated to the sixth century.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://wwwc.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/9804/07/telegram/inrikes8.html |newspaper=[[Aftonbladet]] |title=Silverbibeln daterad med kol-14-metoden |trans-title=Codex Argenteus carbon date determined |location=Uppsala |agency=TT |date=7 April 1998 |access-date=27 March 2017 |language=Swedish}}</ref> It was also determined that the manuscript had been bound at least once during the sixteenth century.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla64/050-132e.htm |title=Silver Bindings carbon dated |access-date=September 24, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319110406/http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla64/050-132e.htm |archive-date=March 19, 2015 |url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n===The Speyer fragment===\nThe final leaf of the codex, fol. 336, was discovered in  October 1970 in [[Speyer]], [[Germany]], 321&nbsp;km south-east of Werden. It was found at the restoration of the  [[Saint Afra]] chapel, rolled around a thin wooden staff, contained in a small [[reliquary]]{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} <!--whos bones contained this reliquary?--> originating in [[Aschaffenburg]]. The leaf contains the final verses of the [[Gospel of Mark]].\n\n===Publications===\nFirst publication mentioning Gothic manuscript appeared in 1569 by [[Goropius Becanus]] in his book ''Origines Antwerpianae'':{{quote|text=So now let us come to another language, which the judgement of every man of distinguished learning at Cologne identifies as Gothic, and examine the aforesaid Lord's Prayer written in that [language] in a volume of great age belonging to the monastery of Werden in the district of Berg, about four miles from Cologne. This [volume] was kindly made available to me, with his notable generosity towards all researchers, by the most reverend and learned [[Maximilien Morillon]], from among the papers of his late brother Antoine.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l0n8QL3crpYC&printsec=frontcover&hl=pl&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Origines Antwerpianae''], Liber VII. Gotodanica: Ex officina Christophori Plantini, 1569, p. 740.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1597, [[Bonaventura Vulcanius]], [[Leiden]] professor of Greek, published his book ''De literis et lingua Getarum sive Gothorum''. It was the first publication of a Gothic text altogether, calling the manuscript \"Codex Argenteus\":\n\n{{quote|text=In regard to this Gothic language, there have come to me [two] brief dissertations by an unidentifiable scholar - shattered planks, as it were, from the shipwreck of the Belgian libraries; the first of these is concerned with the script and pronunciation [of the language], and the other with the Lombardic script which, as he says, he copied from a manuscript codex of great antiquity which he calls \"the Silver\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=GRA8AAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=De+litteris+et+lingua+Getarum&hl=pl&sa=X&ei=LFYcUbzyMan14QTW8oHYCA&ved=0CEEQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false ''De literis et lingua Getarum''], 1597, p.4. Note that according to this Vulcanius did not himself invent the epithet 'Argenteus' but found it in the notes of an unidentified precursor.</ref>}}\n\nBut he was not only the first who enabled the learned world to make the acquaintance of the Gothic translation of the Gospels in Gothic script, but also the first who connected this version with the name of Ulfilas:\n\n{{quote|text=With all due respect to these writers, I should think that the use of Gothic scripts existed among the Goths long before the time of Wulfila but that it was he who first made it known to the Romans by translating the Holy Bible into the Gothic language.  I have heard that a manuscript copy of this, and a very ancient one, written in Gothic capital letters, is lurking in some German library.<ref>''De literis et lingua Getarum'', 1597, p.3</ref>}}\n\n[[Image:Oratio Dominica.jpg|thumb|Part of Lord's Prayer from ''De Literis & Lingva GETARUM Sive GOTHORUM'', 1597, p.33.]]\nIn his book Vulcanius published two chapters about the Gothic language which contained four fragments of the Gothic New Testament: the Ave Maria (Luke I.28 and 42), the Lord's Prayer (Matt. VI.9-13), the Magnificat (Luke I.46-55) and the Song of Simeon (Luke II.29-32), and consistently gave first the Latin translation, then the Gothic in Gothic characters, and then a transliteration of the Gothic in Latin characters.\n\nIn 1737, [[Lars Roberg]], a physician of Uppsala, made a [[woodblock printing|woodcut]] of one page of the manuscript; it was included in [[Henric Benzelius|Benzelius]]' edition of 1750, and the woodcut is preserved in the [[Link\u00f6ping]] Diocesan and Regional Library. Another edition of 1854&ndash;7 by [[Anders Uppstr\u00f6m]] contained an artist's rendition of another page. In 1927, a facsimile edition of the Codex was published.\n\nThe standard edition is that published by [[Wilhelm Streitberg]] in 1910 as ''Die Gotische Bibel'' (''The Gothic Bible'').\n\n==Script and illumination==\n[[File:Detail of Codex Argenteus.jpg|thumb|Detail of Codex Argenteus, Mt 5:34 scan of the 1927 facsimile edition. The highlighted section is an abbreviation of the Gothic cognate of \"[[God (word)|God]]\".]]\nThe manuscript is written in an [[uncial]] script in the [[Gothic alphabet]], reportedly created by [[Ulfilas]].  The script is very uniform, so much so that it has been suggested that it was made with stamps.  However, two hands have been identified: one hand in the Gospels of Matthew and John and another in the Gospels of Mark and Luke. The [[Illuminated manuscript|illumination]] is limited to a few large, framed initials and, at the bottom of each page, a silver arcade which encloses the monograms of the four evangelists.\n\n==Contents==\n\n*[[Gospel of Matthew]]: Matthew 5:15-48; 6:1-32; 7:12-29; 8:1-34; 9:1-38; 10:1,23-42; 11:1-25; 26:70-75; 27:1-19,42-66.\n*[[Gospel of John]]: 5:45-47; 6:1-71; 7:1-53; 8:12-59; 9:1-41; 10:1-42; 11:1-47; 12:1-49; 13:11-38; 14:1-31; 15:1-27; 16:1-33; 27:1-26; 28:1-40; 29:1-13.\n*[[Gospel of Luke]] 1:1-80; 2:2-52; 3:1-38; 4:1-44; 5:1-39; 6:1-49; 7:1-50; 8:1-56; 9:1-62; 10:1-30; 14:9-35; 15:1-32; 16:1-24; 17:3-37; 18:1-43; 19:1-48; 20:1-47.\n*[[Gospel of Mark]]: 1:1-45; 2:1-28; 3:1-35; 4:1-41; 5:1-5; 5-43; 6:1-56; 7:1-37; 8:1-38; 9:1-50; 10:1-52; 11:1-33; 12:1-38; 13:16-29; 14:4-72; 15:1-47; 16:1-12 (+ 16:13-20).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Gothic Bible]]\n* [[Gothic language]]\n* [[Purple parchment]]\n* [[Codex Carolinus]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book | title = Codex argenteus Upsalensis jussu Senatus Universitatis phototypice editus | location = Uppsala | year = 1927}}\n* {{Cite book | author = T\u00f6nnes Kleberg | title = The Silver Bible at Uppsala | publisher = Uppsala University Library | location = Uppsala | year = 1984 | isbn = 91-85092-20-7}}\n* {{Cite book | author = Bologna, Giulia | title = Illuminated Manuscripts: The Book before Gutenberg | location = New York | publisher = Crescent Books | year = 1995 | page = 50}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Codex Argenteus}}\n*[http://www.ub.uu.se/about-the-library/exhibitions/codex-argenteus/ Homepage of the Codex Argenteus (Uppsala University Library)]\n*[http://urn.kb.se/resolve?urn=urn:nbn:se:alvin:portal:record-60279 Digital copy of the Codex Argenteus in the Swedish portal for cultural heritage collections, alvin-record:60279]\n*[http://www.wulfila.be/ Wulfila Project] digital library dedicated to the study of Gothic\n* Lars Munkhammar, [https://web.archive.org/web/20150319110406/http://archive.ifla.org/IV/ifla64/050-132e.htm Uppsala University Library, \"Codex Argenteus\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041209053449/http://www.cs.tut.fi/~dla/Codex_Argenteus/Cod_Arg_Bib.html Codex Argenteus Bibliography]\n*[[oldwikisource:Die gotische Bibel|The Gothic Bible]] on [[Wikisource]], Streitberg's edition\n*[http://wikisource.org/wiki/Gothic_Bible_in_Ulfilan_Gothic_Script_with_correct_i Gothic Bible in Gothic script] on Wikisource\n*[http://la.wikisource.org/wiki/Patrologia_Latina_Vol_18_Ulfilas_-_Evangelia the Gothic New Testament] on wikisource, Patrologia Latina edition\n\n[[Category:6th-century biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:6th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Illuminated biblical manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Purple parchment]]\n[[Category:Gothic Bible]]\n[[Category:Ostrogothic Kingdom]]\n[[Category:History of Uppsala]]\n", "name_user": "Dr. Grampinator", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Codex_Argenteus"}
{"title_page": "Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System", "text_new": "{{short description|Transport agency of the US Department of Justice}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline=Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System\n| logo=Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System MD-83 N311FV taking off.jpg\n| logo_size=292px\n| fleet_size=\n| destinations=\n| IATA=-\n| ICAO=DOJ\n| callsign=JUSTICE\n| founded=1995\n| headquarters=\n| Key people=\n| hubs=\n| focus_cities=\n| website=\n|image=|aoc=|frequent_flyer=|parent=Department of Justice|num_employees=|image_size=|caption=}}\n\n[[File:Conair-Marshal.jpg|thumb|A U.S. Marshal on a \"Con Air\" flight.]]\n[[File:United States Marshals Service - JPATS, Air Operations Division, Air Crew.jpg|thumb|Patch of JPATS, Air Operations Division, Air Crew.]]\n\nThe '''Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System''' ('''JPATS'''), nicknamed \"'''Con Air'''\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmarshals.gov/jpats/conair.htm |title=Con Air: America's High-Flying Paddy Wagon |publisher=Usmarshals.gov |date=2004-06-03 |accessdate=2012-03-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207220129/http://www.usmarshals.gov/jpats/conair.htm |archivedate=2012-02-07 }}</ref> or '''ICE Air'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ice.gov/factsheets/ice-air-operations|title=ICE Air Operations|website=www.ice.gov}}</ref> is an agency of the [[federal government of the United States]] charged with the transportation of persons in legal custody among [[prison]]s, detention centers, courthouses, and other locations.  It is the largest prison transport network in the world.<ref name=\"wired\">{{citation |title=Relocating Prisoners |last=Graves |first=Lucas |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=June 2010 |volume=18 |issue=6 |pages=148\u2013149|url=https://www.wired.com/magazine/2010/05/process_prisoners/}}</ref>  Though primarily used by the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] or [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]], JPATS also assists [[military police|military]] and state law enforcement.\n\nThe agency is managed by the [[United States Marshals Service]] out of the JPATS headquarters in [[Kansas City, Missouri]].<ref name=\"wired\" />  JPATS was formed in 1995 from the merger of the Marshals Service air fleet with that of the [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]].  JPATS completes more than 260,000 prisoner/alien movements per year.<ref name=\"usmarshals.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmarshals.gov/jpats/|title=U.S. Marshals Service|first=U. S. Marshals|last=Service (USMS)|website=www.usmarshals.gov}}</ref>  Air fleet operations are located in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]], with hubs in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]; [[Puerto Rico]] and the [[Virgin Islands]]. Additionally, the [[Federal Transfer Center, Oklahoma City|Federal Transfer Center]] at Oklahoma City's [[Will Rogers World Airport]] was built especially to facilitate prisoner transport on JPATS.\n\nUsually, the [[airline]] employs [[Boeing 737-400]] aircraft to transport convicts and illegal residents of the [[United States]] for extradition.  Smaller jets and turboprops are also used to transport individual prisoners who are considered particularly dangerous or notorious, as well as individuals in the witness protection program.\n\nAccording to the Boeing Jetliner Databook, JPATS operates three Boeing 737s. JPATS also operates an additional [[Saab 2000|Saab 2000 turboprop]].<ref name=\"http://registry.faa.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://registry.faa.gov/aircraftinquiry/NNum_Results.aspx?NNumbertxt=92225|title=FAA Registry - Aircraft - N-Number Inquiry|website=registry.faa.gov}}</ref>\n\nJPATS aircraft use the [[International Civil Aviation Organization|ICAO]] designator '''DOJ''' with the callsign '''JUSTICE'''.\n\nImmediately after the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]], when the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] [[Closings and cancellations following the September 11, 2001 attacks#Travel effects|grounded all civilian air service]], JPATS was the only civilian passenger-carrying air service allowed to continue flying in U.S. airspace.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n==History and evolution==\nPrior to the existence of JPATS, the air transport of federal inmates over long distances was complicated. The process required an escort by two U.S. Marshals, accompanying the inmate on a regular passenger airplane. This posed numerous problems, including danger to civilians, a backlog of marshals needed to perform such escorts, and a high taxpayer expense.\n\nIn the early 1970s, the U.S. Marshals were offered a transfer from the [[Federal Aviation Administration|Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)]] of a [[Boeing 727]] aircraft. Though no purpose was originally designated for this plane, one official had the idea of using it for the mass transportation of federal inmates. JPATS' predecessor was the ''National Prisoner Transportation System'' of the U.S. Marshals Service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmarshals.gov/history/npts/index.html |title=U.S. Marshals Service, History, National Prisoner Transportation System |publisher=Usmarshals.gov |date=1985-08-20 |accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe airline ultimately improved the efficiency of inmate transportation and made the sight of a shackled commercial airline passenger largely a thing of the past. For a plane full of 200 inmates, only 12 marshals are required. Marshals are trained with aircraft emergency procedures very similar to those [[flight attendant]]s learn to protect the aircraft's occupants.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Today==\n[[File:JPATS-prisoners stepping down an aircraft.jpg|thumb|Prisoners deplaning|right|upright=1.15]]\nToday's{{When|date=November 2019}} JPATS fleet has expanded to three full-sized aircraft.<ref name=\"wired\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mro-network.com/maintenance-repair-overhaul/aar-maintain-aircraft-us-marshals-service|title=AAR to Maintain Aircraft for U.S. Marshals Service|date=2018-12-04|website=MRO Network|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> These planes fly a large series of routes that serve nearly every major U.S. city.<ref name=\"usmarshals.gov\"/>\n\nThe flight schedules are kept secret from the public, and are known only to those directly involved in its operation. Inmates scheduled to fly are given little or no advance notice of their flight, to deter escapes and sabotage, and to prevent harm from outsiders.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:\"blue box\" handcuff cover.jpg|left|thumb|189x189px|Prisoner in handcuffs augmented with a handcuff cover and belly chains]]\nPassengers aboard a flight are [[physical restraints|restrained]] with [[handcuffs]] as well as [[Fetters|ankle]] and [[Belly chain (restraint)|waist chains]] which are double- or even triple-locked. Those who pose additional danger may be forced to wear additional restraints, such as reinforced mittens that completely isolate and almost completely immobilize the hands, [[handcuff cover]]s which conceal the keyholes, and face masks to prevent biting and spitting. However, due to [[FAA]] regulations inmates are not physically restrained to their seats in any way except for seat belts used during takeoff and landing.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\nFlight and seating arrangements are made carefully with the intent to separate inmates who may  conflict with one another. Members of rival prison gangs may be transported on different days to help reduce the risk of an in-flight incident.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\nUnlike the practice of most jails, male and female inmates fly together on the same planes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kerman|first1=Piper|title=Orange is the New Black, My Time in a Women's Prison|date=2010|publisher=Abacus|location=London|isbn=978-0-3491-3987-6|page=193|edition=2013}}</ref>\n\n==Pop culture references==\n*''[[Con Air]]'' (1997) starring [[Nicolas Cage]] draws heavy inspiration and basis from the operations on this agency, with the title being a reference to the agency's nickname. The movie portrayed the interior of the plane (a [[C-123 Provider]], which JPATS does not operate) as a much steelier, more prison-like environment than a typical JPATS 727, which in reality looks much like any other airliner. The storyline of the film covers this by saying that the prisoners on this flight are 'the worst of the worst' including several serial killers and mass murderers.\n*''[[U.S. Marshals (film)|U.S. Marshals]]'' (1998) depicted the story of a JPATS flight 343, a Boeing 727-200 that crashed during flight and the manhunt for a prisoner who escapes following the crash.\n* An episode of the cartoon ''[[Freakazoid!]]'' takes place on a plane spoofing this airline called \"Prison Air.\"\n*''[[The Unusuals]]'' (television show) episode \"The Dentist\" (2009), Det. Eddie Alvarez asks suspended U.S. Marshal and suspected felon Ben Foster if he will be transporting a prisoner via \"JPATS\". Marshal Foster appears confused until Det. Alvarez explains that it is the \"Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System\". Marshal Foster then confirms the prisoner will be transported via JPATS, however he is really breaking the prisoner out of custody after robbing the police precinct of valuable evidence against a dentist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1422565/|title=The Dentist|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>\n*''[[Orange Is the New Black]]'' (television show) episode \"Thirsty Bird\" (2014), prisoner [[Piper Chapman]] is transported on a JPATS plane for a transfer from Litchfield prison in New York to a Chicago detention facility. US Marshals are shown doing prisoner pat-downs before boarding and then staffing the flight. Prisoners are shown boarding the flight from various locations, including both male and female.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080916073926/http://www.ice.gov/partners/dro/airtran.htm U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement - Air Transportation]\n{{refend}}\n* Increasing the local use of the US Marshals Service Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System (JPATS)/Ingo Remo Johnson (Author), Publisher: Western Baptist College, January 1, 1994, ASIN: B0006RI4HS /  [https://www.amazon.co.uk/Increasing-Marshalls-Service-Prisoner-Transportation/dp/B0006RI4HS Increasing the local use of the US Marshalls Service Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System]\n\nOut of Orange:A Memoir \u2013 HarperCollins, May 5, 2015 by Cleary Wolters (Author) {{ISBN|0062376152}}, 9780062376152\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|United States|Politics|Aviation}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.usmarshals.gov/jpats}}\n\n\n{{Airlines of the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Justice Prisoner And Alien Transportation System}}\n[[Category:Airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Police aviation]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Justice agencies]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1995]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Transport agency of the US Department of Justice}}\n{{Infobox airline\n| airline=Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System\n| logo=Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System MD-83 N311FV taking off.jpg\n| logo_size=292px\n| fleet_size=\n| destinations=\n| IATA=-\n| ICAO=DOJ\n| callsign=JUSTICE\n| founded=1995\n| headquarters=\n| Key people=\n| hubs=\n| focus_cities=\n| website=\n|image=|aoc=|frequent_flyer=|parent=Department of Justice|num_employees=|image_size=|caption=}}\n\n[[File:Conair-Marshal.jpg|thumb|A U.S. Marshal on a \"Con Air\" flight.]]\n[[File:United States Marshals Service - JPATS, Air Operations Division, Air Crew.jpg|thumb|Patch of JPATS, Air Operations Division, Air Crew.]]\n\nThe '''Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System''' ('''JPATS'''), nicknamed \"'''Con Air'''\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmarshals.gov/jpats/conair.htm |title=Con Air: America's High-Flying Paddy Wagon |publisher=Usmarshals.gov |date=2004-06-03 |accessdate=2012-03-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207220129/http://www.usmarshals.gov/jpats/conair.htm |archivedate=2012-02-07 }}</ref> or '''ICE Air'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ice.gov/factsheets/ice-air-operations|title=ICE Air Operations|website=www.ice.gov}}</ref> is an agency of the [[federal government of the United States]] charged with the transportation of persons in legal custody among [[prison]]s, detention centers, courthouses, and other locations.  It is the largest prison transport network in the world.<ref name=\"wired\">{{citation |title=Relocating Prisoners |last=Graves |first=Lucas |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=June 2010 |volume=18 |issue=6 |pages=148\u2013149|url=https://www.wired.com/magazine/2010/05/process_prisoners/}}</ref>  Though primarily used by the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]] or [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]], JPATS also assists [[military police|military]] and state law enforcement.\n\nThe agency is managed by the [[United States Marshals Service]] out of the JPATS headquarters in [[Kansas City, Missouri]].<ref name=\"wired\" />  JPATS was formed in 1995 from the merger of the Marshals Service air fleet with that of the [[Immigration and Naturalization Service]].  JPATS completes more than 260,000 prisoner/alien movements per year.<ref name=\"usmarshals.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmarshals.gov/jpats/|title=U.S. Marshals Service|first=U. S. Marshals|last=Service (USMS)|website=www.usmarshals.gov}}</ref>  Air fleet operations are located in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]], with hubs in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]; [[Puerto Rico]] and the [[Virgin Islands]]. Additionally, the [[Federal Transfer Center, Oklahoma City|Federal Transfer Center]] at Oklahoma City's [[Will Rogers World Airport]] was built especially to facilitate prisoner transport on JPATS.\n\nUsually, the [[airline]] employs [[Boeing 737-400]] aircraft to transport convicts and illegal residents of the [[United States]] for extradition.  Smaller jets and turboprops are also used to transport individual prisoners who are considered particularly dangerous or notorious, as well as individuals in the witness protection program.\n\nAccording to the Boeing Jetliner Databook, JPATS operates three Boeing 737s. JPATS also operates an additional [[Saab 2000|Saab 2000 turboprop]].<ref name=\"http://registry.faa.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://registry.faa.gov/aircraftinquiry/NNum_Results.aspx?NNumbertxt=92225|title=FAA Registry - Aircraft - N-Number Inquiry|website=registry.faa.gov}}</ref>\n\nJPATS aircraft use the [[International Civil Aviation Organization|ICAO]] designator '''DOJ''' with the callsign '''JUSTICE'''.\n\nImmediately after the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]], when the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] [[Closings and cancellations following the September 11, 2001 attacks#Travel effects|grounded all civilian air service]], JPATS was the only civilian passenger-carrying air service allowed to continue flying in U.S. airspace.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n==History and evolution==\nPrior to the existence of JPATS, the air transport of federal inmates over long distances was complicated. The process required an escort by two U.S. Marshals, accompanying the inmate on a regular passenger airplane. This posed numerous problems, including danger to civilians, a backlog of marshals needed to perform such escorts, and a high taxpayer expense.\n\nIn the early 1970s, the U.S. Marshals were offered a transfer from the [[Federal Aviation Administration|Federal Aviation Administration (FAA)]] of a [[Boeing 727]] aircraft. Though no purpose was originally designated for this plane, one official had the idea of using it for the mass transportation of federal inmates. JPATS' predecessor was the ''National Prisoner Transportation System'' of the U.S. Marshals Service.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmarshals.gov/history/npts/index.html |title=U.S. Marshals Service, History, National Prisoner Transportation System |publisher=Usmarshals.gov |date=1985-08-20 |accessdate=2012-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe airline ultimately improved the efficiency of inmate transportation and made the sight of a shackled commercial airline passenger largely a thing of the past. For a plane full of 200 inmates, only 12 marshals are required. Marshals are trained with aircraft emergency procedures very similar to those [[flight attendant]]s learn to protect the aircraft's occupants.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Today==\n[[File:JPATS-prisoners stepping down an aircraft.jpg|thumb|Prisoners deplaning|right|upright=1.15]]\nToday's{{When|date=November 2019}} JPATS fleet has expanded to three full-sized aircraft.<ref name=\"wired\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mro-network.com/maintenance-repair-overhaul/aar-maintain-aircraft-us-marshals-service|title=AAR to Maintain Aircraft for U.S. Marshals Service|date=2018-12-04|website=MRO Network|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref> These planes fly a large series of routes that serve nearly every major U.S. city.<ref name=\"usmarshals.gov\"/>\n\nThe flight schedules are kept secret from the public, and are known only to those directly involved in its operation. Inmates scheduled to fly are given little or no advance notice of their flight, to deter escapes and sabotage, and to prevent harm from outsiders.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:\"blue box\" handcuff cover.jpg|left|thumb|189x189px|Prisoner in handcuffs augmented with a handcuff cover and belly chains]]\nPassengers aboard a flight are [[physical restraints|restrained]] with [[handcuffs]] as well as [[Fetters|ankle]] and [[Belly chain (restraint)|waist chains]] which are double- or even triple-locked. Those who pose additional danger may be forced to wear additional restraints, such as reinforced mittens that completely isolate and almost completely immobilize the hands, [[handcuff cover]]s which conceal the keyholes, and face masks to prevent biting and spitting. However, due to [[FAA]] regulations inmates are not physically restrained to their seats in any way except for seat belts used during takeoff and landing.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\nFlight and seating arrangements are made carefully with the intent to separate inmates who may  conflict with one another. Members of rival prison gangs may be transported on different days to help reduce the risk of an in-flight incident.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\nUnlike the practice of most jails, male and female inmates fly together on the same planes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kerman|first1=Piper|title=Orange is the New Black, My Time in a Women's Prison|date=2010|publisher=Abacus|location=London|isbn=978-0-3491-3987-6|page=193|edition=2013}}</ref>\n\n==Pop culture references==\n*''[[Con Air]]'' (1997) starring [[Nicolas Cage]] draws heavy inspiration and basis from the operations on this agency, with the title being a reference to the agency's nickname. The movie portrayed the interior of the plane (a [[C-123 Provider]], which JPATS does not operate) as a much steelier, more prison-like environment than a typical JPATS 727, which in reality looks much like any other airliner. The storyline of the film covers this by saying that the prisoners on this flight are 'the worst of the worst' including several serial killers and mass murderers.\n*''[[U.S. Marshals (film)|U.S. Marshals]]'' (1998) depicted the story of a JPATS flight 343, a Boeing 727-200 that crashed during flight and the manhunt for a prisoner who escapes following the crash.\n* An episode of the cartoon ''[[Freakazoid!]]'' takes place on a plane spoofing this airline called \"Prison Air.\"\n*''[[The Unusuals]]'' (television show) episode \"The Dentist\" (2009), Det. Eddie Alvarez asks suspended U.S. Marshal and suspected felon Ben Foster if he will be transporting a prisoner via \"JPATS\". Marshal Foster appears confused until Det. Alvarez explains that it is the \"Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System\". Marshal Foster then confirms the prisoner will be transported via JPATS, however he is really breaking the prisoner out of custody after robbing the police precinct of valuable evidence against a dentist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1422565/|title=The Dentist|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>\n*''[[Orange Is the New Black]]'' (television show) episode \"Thirsty Bird\" (2014), prisoner [[Piper Chapman]] is transported on a JPATS plane for a transfer from Litchfield prison in New York to a Chicago detention facility. US Marshals are shown doing prisoner pat-downs before boarding and then staffing the flight. Prisoners are shown boarding the flight from various locations, including both male and female.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080916073926/http://www.ice.gov/partners/dro/airtran.htm U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement - Air Transportation]\n{{refend}}\n* Increasing the local use of the US Marshals Service Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System (JPATS)/Ingo Remo Johnson (Author), Publisher: Western Baptist College, January 1, 1994, ASIN: B0006RI4HS /  [https://www.amazon.co.uk/Increasing-Marshalls-Service-Prisoner-Transportation/dp/B0006RI4HS Increasing the local use of the US Marshalls Service Justice Prisoner and Alien Transportation System]\n\nOut of Orange:A Memoir \u2013 HarperCollins, May 5, 2015 by Cleary Wolters (Author) {{ISBN|0062376152}}, 9780062376152\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|United States|Politics|Aviation}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n\n{{Airlines of the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Justice Prisoner And Alien Transportation System}}\n[[Category:Airlines of the United States]]\n[[Category:Police aviation]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Justice agencies]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1995]]\n", "name_user": "WurmWoode", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Tweaks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justice_Prisoner_and_Alien_Transportation_System"}
{"title_page": "In Medias Res (Krypteria album)", "text_new": "I have just wanted something different {{Infobox album\n| name       = In Medias Res\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Krypteria]]\n| cover      = Krypteria In Medias Res.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 25 July 2005\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Symphonic rock]], [[symphonic metal]]\n| length     = 53:50\n| label      = Synergy Records / [[EMI]]\n| producer   = Christoph Siemons\n| prev_title = [[Krypteria (album)|Krypteria]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Evolution Principle]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = In Medias Res\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Victoriam Speramus\n | single1date = 2005\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''In Medias Res''''' is a studio album by the German [[symphonic metal]] band [[Krypteria]], released in 2005. The album was released as an [[enhanced CD]], which includes two video tracks: \"Victoriam Speramus\", \"Get the Hell Out of My Way\".\n\nThe album name (Latin for ''Into the middle of things'') reflects the fact, that the band considers ''In Medias Res'' their first album,<ref>[http://www.krypteria.de/?r=1 Official Krypteria discography.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509234619/http://www.krypteria.de/?r=1 |date=2011-05-09 }} Note the *** on ''Liberatio'' which are explained on the album page.</ref> while the band has worked together as Krypteria since 2001.\n\n''In Medias Res'' peaked at position 66 of the [[Media Control Charts|German album charts]]<ref name=MCCalbum>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Krypteria/13732/?type=longplay |title=Krypteria Longplay-Chartverfolgung |work=musicline.de |publisher=PHONONET GmbH |accessdate=24 April 2012 |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204014520/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Krypteria/13732/?type=longplay |archive-date=4 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and at position 86 in [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austria]].<ref name=AT>{{cite web|url=http://www.austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Krypteria |title=Krypteria in der \u00f6sterreichischen Hitparade |language=German |work=austriancharts.at |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=24 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = \n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = \n| total_length    =\n\n| all_writing = Christoph Siemons and S.C. Kuschnerus, except where indicated\n| title1         =Victoriam Speramus (Original Album Ver.)\n| length1         =3:55\n| title2         =Will You Be There for Me\n| length2         =4:43\n| title3         =Why\n| length3         =4:43\n| title4         =No More Lies\n| length4         =3:45\n| title5         =Quae Laetitia\n| length5         =4:38 \n| title6         =Always and Forever\n| length6         =4:37\n| title7         =Concordia\n| length7         =4:01\n| title8         =Save Me\n| length8         =3:26\n| title9         =Animus Liber \n| note9          =Frank Stumvoll, Kuschnerus\n| length9         =5:00\n| title10         =You & I\n| note10          =Siemons, [[Ji-In Cho]], Kuschnerus\n| length10        =5:07\n| title11         =Going My Way\n| length11         =3:10\n| title12         =The Tears I Cry\n| note12          =Siemons, Cho, Kuschnerus\n| length12         =3:57\n| title13         =[[Carol of the Bells]]\n| note13          = arr. [[George Winston]], bonus track\n| length13         =2:48\n}}\n\n==Credits==\n*[[Ji-In Cho]] \u2013 vocals, piano\n*Christoph Siemons \u2013 guitars, keyboards\n*Frank Stumvoll \u2013 bass, backing vocals \n*S.C. Kuschnerus \u2013 drums, backing vocals, lead vocals on \"You & I\"\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*{{cite web|url={{allmusic|id=r1228470|class=album|pure_url=yes}} |title=In Media Res \u2013 Krypteria |work=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=2011-04-19}}\n\n{{Krypteria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:In Medias Res (Krypteria Album)}}\n[[Category:Krypteria albums]]\n[[Category:2005 albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-metal-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = In Medias Res\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Krypteria]]\n| cover      = Krypteria In Medias Res.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 25 July 2005\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Symphonic rock]], [[symphonic metal]]\n| length     = 53:50\n| label      = Synergy Records / [[EMI]]\n| producer   = Christoph Siemons\n| prev_title = [[Krypteria (album)|Krypteria]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Evolution Principle]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = In Medias Res\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Victoriam Speramus\n | single1date = 2005\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''In Medias Res''''' is a studio album by the German [[symphonic metal]] band [[Krypteria]], released in 2005. The album was released as an [[enhanced CD]], which includes two video tracks: \"Victoriam Speramus\", \"Get the Hell Out of My Way\".\n\nThe album name (Latin for ''Into the middle of things'') reflects the fact, that the band considers ''In Medias Res'' their first album,<ref>[http://www.krypteria.de/?r=1 Official Krypteria discography.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110509234619/http://www.krypteria.de/?r=1 |date=2011-05-09 }} Note the *** on ''Liberatio'' which are explained on the album page.</ref> while the band has worked together as Krypteria since 2001.\n\n''In Medias Res'' peaked at position 66 of the [[Media Control Charts|German album charts]]<ref name=MCCalbum>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Krypteria/13732/?type=longplay |title=Krypteria Longplay-Chartverfolgung |work=musicline.de |publisher=PHONONET GmbH |accessdate=24 April 2012 |language=German |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111204014520/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Krypteria/13732/?type=longplay |archive-date=4 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and at position 86 in [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austria]].<ref name=AT>{{cite web|url=http://www.austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Krypteria |title=Krypteria in der \u00f6sterreichischen Hitparade |language=German |work=austriancharts.at |publisher=Hung Medien |accessdate=24 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = \n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = \n| total_length    =\n\n| all_writing = Christoph Siemons and S.C. Kuschnerus, except where indicated\n| title1         =Victoriam Speramus (Original Album Ver.)\n| length1         =3:55\n| title2         =Will You Be There for Me\n| length2         =4:43\n| title3         =Why\n| length3         =4:43\n| title4         =No More Lies\n| length4         =3:45\n| title5         =Quae Laetitia\n| length5         =4:38 \n| title6         =Always and Forever\n| length6         =4:37\n| title7         =Concordia\n| length7         =4:01\n| title8         =Save Me\n| length8         =3:26\n| title9         =Animus Liber \n| note9          =Frank Stumvoll, Kuschnerus\n| length9         =5:00\n| title10         =You & I\n| note10          =Siemons, [[Ji-In Cho]], Kuschnerus\n| length10        =5:07\n| title11         =Going My Way\n| length11         =3:10\n| title12         =The Tears I Cry\n| note12          =Siemons, Cho, Kuschnerus\n| length12         =3:57\n| title13         =[[Carol of the Bells]]\n| note13          = arr. [[George Winston]], bonus track\n| length13         =2:48\n}}\n\n==Credits==\n*[[Ji-In Cho]] \u2013 vocals, piano\n*Christoph Siemons \u2013 guitars, keyboards\n*Frank Stumvoll \u2013 bass, backing vocals \n*S.C. Kuschnerus \u2013 drums, backing vocals, lead vocals on \"You & I\"\n\n==References==\n<references />\n*{{cite web|url={{allmusic|id=r1228470|class=album|pure_url=yes}} |title=In Media Res \u2013 Krypteria |work=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=2011-04-19}}\n\n{{Krypteria}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:In Medias Res (Krypteria Album)}}\n[[Category:Krypteria albums]]\n[[Category:2005 albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-metal-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Comorossi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_Medias_Res_(Krypteria_album)"}
{"title_page": "Duke Elvis", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Duke Elvis|timestamp=20200425201458|year=2020|month=April|day=25|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Duke Elvis|date=25 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n'''Duke Elvis''' is a [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] actor, model and movie producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm10742445/|title=Elvis Duke|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> He is predominantly known for his role as ABULU in [[Africa Magic]] TV series [[The Johnsons (Nigerian TV series)|The Johnsons]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Johnsons (Nigerian TV series)|date=2019-12-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Johnsons_(Nigerian_TV_series)&oldid=929147486|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=The Johnsons|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10437170/|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Duke Elvis\n| image              = IMG-20200302-WA0013.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Nwankwo Onyekachi Duke\n| birth_date         = March 3, 1987\n| birth_place        = Enugu State\n| nationality        = Nigerian\n| occupation         = Actor, Model, movie producer\n| years_active       = 2006, 2011-present\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nDuke was born and grew up in the eastern part of Nigeria, [[Enugu State]] precisely. He was born into an average Nigerian family and he is the fourth child in a family of five children, his parents were civil servants and as such they believe so much in education and discipline.\n\nHe was a very active member of his secondary school's drama club and subsequently he became the social prefect of his school. He was also part of a young, passionate and aspiring actors theater group called WORLD AFRICAN THEATER. He and the other members of this theater group would write to schools so as to get chances of acting what they had rehearsed live on stage for other students to watch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribuneonlineng.com/government-should-get-more-involved-in-nollywood-elvis-duke/|title=Government should get more involved in Nollywood \u2013Elvis Duke|date=2020-03-20|website=Tribune Online|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nDuke pursued his university education at [[Enugu State University of Science and Technology]] where he bagged his B.sc in civil engineering.\n\n== Career ==\nHis professional acting career kicked off in 2006 when he made his [[Nollywood]] debut and played the character BEN in the movie MAN IN THE MIDDLE which featured other Nollywood prominent names [[Oge Okoye]], [[Zack Orji]] and [[Rita Dominic]]. He also starred in another movie TRUE LIES and since then he has been in quite a number of movies as well as an [[African magic|African Magic]] TV series known as [[The Johnsons (Nigerian TV series)|The Johnsons]]. He is currently working on his first movie production.\n\n== Selected Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''MOVIES'''\n!Title\n!Note\n|-\n|Man in the middle\n|Played the role BEN\nMovie also Featuring: [[Zack Orji]], [[Tonto Dikeh|Tonto Dike]], [[Rita Dominic]]\n|-\n|Happyness Limited<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nollywoodreinvented.com/2017/08/happyness-limited.html|title=The Happy.ness Ltd|last=nollywoodreinvented|date=2017-08-19|website=Nollywood REinvented|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n|Also featuring: [[Kiki Omeili]]\n|-\n|Born<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iffr.com/en/2018/films/born|title=Born|date=2018-01-15|website=IFFR|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n|Feature film Produced by Micheal Omonua\n|-\n|Bias\n|Feature film\n|-\n|Mystified<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://batatv.com/2018/04/13/mystified-latest-2018-intriguing-nollywood-movie-kenneth-okolie-stan-nze-esther-audu/|title=Mystified- Latest 2018 Intriguing Nollywood Movie {{!}}Kenneth Okolie{{!}} Stan Nze{{!}} Esther Audu{{!}}|last=BataTV|date=2018-04-13|website=BataTV Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n|Also featuring: Esther Audu, [[Kenneth Okolie]]\n|-\n|The Herbert Macaulay Affair<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mnr.com.ng/(X(1)S(raym2mildvax110si2xochpw))/Mobile/Movies/1451/The-Herbert-Macaulay-Affair?fbclid=IwAR1_Bcm0PADtK0zX4EA11-lxORWlCvvhvMi5z1p2DKh67Xo0n-kSdNK4KFc|title=The Herbert Macaulay Affair {{!}} MNR.com.ng|website=www.mnr.com.ng|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n|Directed by Imoh Umoren\n|-\n|The Man Who Cuts Tattoos<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whatson.bfi.org.uk/lff/Online/manwhocutstattoos|title=The Man Who Cuts Tattoos|website=BFI London Film Festival 2019|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n|Feature Film Prod by Abba Makama\n|-\n|Heart\n|Feature film\n|-\n|Brotherly\n|Feature film\n|-\n|Sleep Away\n|Feature film\n|-\n|True Lies\n|Feature film\n|-\n|JujuStories\n|Feature film, currently In post production\n|-\n|Deep Cover\n|In Post Production, Prod by Duke Elvis and [[Whochey Nnamdi]]\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''SERIES'''\n!Title\n!Note\n|-\n|The Johnsons<ref>{{Citation|title=The Johnsons|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10437170/|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n|Presently playing the role of ABULU in [[The Johnsons (Nigerian TV series)|The Johnsons]] TV series on [[Africa Magic]]\nProduced by Native Media TV. Featuring: [[Samuel Ajibola]], [[Ada Ameh]], [[Charles Inojie|Charles Inogie]], [[Chinedu Ikedieze]] etc.\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Duke Elvis|timestamp=20200425201458|year=2020|month=April|day=25|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Duke Elvis|date=25 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n'''Duke Elvis''' is a [[Nigerians|Nigerian]] actor, model and movie producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm10742445/|title=Elvis Duke|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> He is predominantly known for his role as ABULU in [[Africa Magic]] TV series [[The Johnsons (Nigerian TV series)|The Johnsons]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Johnsons (Nigerian TV series)|date=2019-12-03|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=The_Johnsons_(Nigerian_TV_series)&oldid=929147486|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=The Johnsons|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10437170/|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Duke Elvis\n| image              = IMG-20200302-WA0013.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Nwankwo Onyekachi Duke\n| birth_date         = March 3, 1987\n| birth_place        = Enugu State\n| nationality        = Nigerian\n| occupation         = Actor, Model, movie producer\n| years_active       = 2006, 2011-present\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nDuke was born and grew up in the eastern part of Nigeria, [[Enugu State]] precisely. He was born into an average Nigerian family and he is the fourth child in a family of five children, his parents were civil servants and as such they believe so much in education and discipline.\n\nHe was a very active member of his secondary school's drama club and subsequently he became the social prefect of his school. He was also part of a young, passionate and aspiring actors theater group called WORLD AFRICAN THEATER. He and the other members of this theater group would write to schools so as to get chances of acting what they had rehearsed live on stage for other students to watch.\n\n== Education ==\nDuke pursued his university education at [[Enugu State University of Science and Technology]] where he bagged his B.sc in civil engineering.\n\n== Career ==\nHis professional acting career kicked off in 2006 when he made his [[Nollywood]] debut and played the character BEN in the movie MAN IN THE MIDDLE which featured other Nollywood prominent names [[Oge Okoye]], [[Zack Orji]] and [[Rita Dominic]]. He also starred in another movie TRUE LIES and since then he has been in quite a number of movies as well as an [[African magic|African Magic]] TV series known as [[The Johnsons (Nigerian TV series)|The Johnsons]]. He is currently working on his first movie production.\n\n== Selected Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+'''MOVIES'''\n!Title\n!Note\n|-\n|Man in the middle\n|Played the role BEN\nMovie also Featuring: [[Zack Orji]], [[Tonto Dikeh|Tonto Dike]], [[Rita Dominic]]\n|-\n|Happyness Limited<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nollywoodreinvented.com/2017/08/happyness-limited.html|title=The Happy.ness Ltd|last=nollywoodreinvented|date=2017-08-19|website=Nollywood REinvented|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n|Also featuring: [[Kiki Omeili]]\n|-\n|Born<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://iffr.com/en/2018/films/born|title=Born|date=2018-01-15|website=IFFR|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n|Feature film Produced by Micheal Omonua\n|-\n|Bias\n|Feature film\n|-\n|Mystified<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://batatv.com/2018/04/13/mystified-latest-2018-intriguing-nollywood-movie-kenneth-okolie-stan-nze-esther-audu/|title=Mystified- Latest 2018 Intriguing Nollywood Movie {{!}}Kenneth Okolie{{!}} Stan Nze{{!}} Esther Audu{{!}}|last=BataTV|date=2018-04-13|website=BataTV Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n|Also featuring: Esther Audu, [[Kenneth Okolie]]\n|-\n|The Herbert Macaulay Affair<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mnr.com.ng/(X(1)S(raym2mildvax110si2xochpw))/Mobile/Movies/1451/The-Herbert-Macaulay-Affair?fbclid=IwAR1_Bcm0PADtK0zX4EA11-lxORWlCvvhvMi5z1p2DKh67Xo0n-kSdNK4KFc|title=The Herbert Macaulay Affair {{!}} MNR.com.ng|website=www.mnr.com.ng|access-date=